1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,760
My SQL Kafka riddies, they can't just be any PAD, they need to be the same PAD, that's

2
00:00:07,760 --> 00:00:09,760
stateful sets.

3
00:00:09,760 --> 00:00:14,800
Deployment PADs are interchangeable, random names, replaceable.

4
00:00:14,800 --> 00:00:20,280
Stateful set PADs are sticky, mydb0 is always mydb0.

5
00:00:20,280 --> 00:00:25,520
Same name, same storage, same identity, even across rescheduling.

6
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:29,760
PADs are created in order, 0, then 1, then 2.

7
00:00:29,760 --> 00:00:34,120
Reveal down in reverse, rolling updates 1 at a time.

8
00:00:34,120 --> 00:00:37,880
This prevents split brain in clustered databases.

9
00:00:37,880 --> 00:00:41,960
Each PAD gets its own persistent volume claim.

10
00:00:41,960 --> 00:00:47,760
Deleting the stateful set does not delete the volumes, your data stays safe.

11
00:00:47,760 --> 00:00:50,720
Stateless workload, use a deployment.

12
00:00:50,720 --> 00:00:56,080
Need stable identity and persistent storage, stateful set.

13
00:00:56,080 --> 00:00:57,880
Databases live here.

14
00:00:57,880 --> 00:01:01,000
Run the docs, Kubernetes, stateful sets.

